text: I think there's lots to be said about the different player groups between Oathbreaker and cEDH. THe players that wanted the RC to make PW's as commanders didn't like the decision so they decided to make their own format exactly how they wanted it with it's own ban list and all that, while the cEDH crowd just keeps tweeting that they wantthe RC to run the format with them in mind rather than forming a distinction between the formats. Looking at how quickly Oathbreaker is starting to pickup vs the view of cEDH remaining largely the same. Even talking to Cameron the other day just reinforced that while the players may not mean to cross the streams, it still needs to be treated like a separate format altogether since he was always referencing his "casual decks" as decks he wouldn't play w/ his competitive friends and his competitive decks he wouldn't play with casuals etc. There's already a line drawn, it's just people wanting to remain in the gray area is what it feels like.
It'll be interesting to see if Oathbreaker sticks around for a minute.

It's got a backyard game feel to it. Remember those weird games you and your friends would make as kids? It's Garageball, where you have to bounce the tennis ball off the garage door and try to catch it and and then make a basket, but if it goes in the rain gutter you lose 5 points. Garageball was a great game with your friend Mikey and your younger brother and you guys had a blast. But it also really doesn't scale or work that well outside you and your friends in your backyard when you were eleven.
